<TITLE> Food security workshop begins Thursday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 8 (bdnews24.com)A one-day food security workshop for senior officials from the government, Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), development partners and civil society will be held on Thursday. Funded by the U.S. government, workshop is part of a series of research workshops organized under the "National Food Policy Capacity Strengthening Program (NFPCSP)", a $7.4 million initiative, funded jointly by the United States Agency for International Development (USAID) and the European Union. The project works with the government to enhance its capacity to oversee a comprehensive, equitable, gender-sensitive, and poverty-targeted National Food Policy, said a US embassy press release on Wednesday. A core objective of the NFPCSP is to expand and deepen the capacity of civil society policy makers and researchers to conduct high-quality research to enrich the implementation of the National Food Policy. Participants will discuss and share results of the completed research studies under the NFPCSP, jointly administered by the government and FAO, and will propose recommendations to the government to better implement the National Food Policy. The NFPCSP workshop marks another step forward in collaboration between the government, development partners, and civil society to ensure food security for all in Bangladesh, the release said. The NFPCSP promotes dialogue within civil society on issues facing those most vulnerable to food insecurity. It also supports stronger links between policy analysts and researchers in academia and civil society. The US government has provided more than $5 billion in development assistance to Bangladesh since 1971, more than one half of which was in the form of food 
